\begin{abstract}
\textit{Objective:}
Diagnostic delays in intensive care units (ICUs) pose a critical
patient-safety risk. Existing clinical decision support systems
rely on static temporal thresholds that cannot adapt to
patient-specific workflow variability. This paper aims to
develop an agentic framework that learns expected diagnostic
timing from electronic health records (EHRs) and detects delays
as deviations from those learned expectations.

\textit{Methods:}
The Agentic Clinical Workflow Intelligence System (ACWIS) is
proposed. It extracts physiological instability trigger events
from vital sign streams, aligns each trigger with subsequent
laboratory events using a three-level fallback strategy, and
models delay distributions using a two-layer long short-term
memory (LSTM) network trained on ten temporal features from the
MIMIC-IV ICU database. A LangGraph-based agentic multi-agent
layer implements a reactive pipeline evaluating deviation after
laboratory completion, and a proactive pipeline issuing early
warnings before completion. Detected deviations are classified
into four severity levels, and a large language model (LLM)
agent generates clinician-readable explanations.

\textit{Results:}
Evaluated on 703,808 trigger-level records, ACWIS achieves a
mean absolute error (MAE) of 89.93 minutes, a root mean square
error (RMSE) of 166.69 minutes, and a 2.3\% MAE improvement
over the mean-predictor baseline. The model performs best on
short delays (MAE under 50 minutes for delays under 3 hours,
comprising 82\% of the dataset). The proactive pipeline
demonstrates pre-event alerting capability across multiple ICU
stays.

\textit{Conclusion:}
ACWIS provides rule-free, learned clinical workflow delay
detection with dual reactive and proactive agentic monitoring,
validated on a large-scale ICU dataset.

\textit{Significance:}
This work represents the first integration of learned LSTM-based
delay prediction with LangGraph-orchestrated dual-pipeline
agentic monitoring for ICU diagnostic workflow intelligence.
\end{abstract}

