\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
%%===========================================================

Intensive care units (ICUs) generate continuous time-stamped
clinical data---vital sign measurements, laboratory orders,
medication administrations, and procedural events---that
collectively constitute longitudinal clinical workflows
reflecting how patient care progresses during a hospital stay.
In high-acuity environments, timely workflow execution is
directly linked to patient outcomes: delays in completing
diagnostic laboratory investigations following physiological
instability events have been associated with increased
mortality, prolonged length of stay, and avoidable
complications~\cite{ref1,ref4}.

Despite the richness of electronic health record (EHR) data,
automated detection of clinical workflow delays remains an open
problem. Existing clinical decision support systems (CDSS)
address this through predefined temporal rules that flag any
laboratory result arriving beyond a fixed time limit as a
delay. Such systems suffer from three fundamental limitations.
First, they cannot adapt to patient-specific variability in
expected care timing, which depends on disease severity,
comorbidities, and clinical context. Second, they operate
exclusively retrospectively, detecting delays only after they
have fully materialized with no capacity for anticipatory
warning. Third, they cannot learn normal workflow timing
patterns from historical data, making them brittle as clinical
practice evolves.

Recent advances in temporal deep learning on EHR data have
shown that long short-term memory (LSTM) networks and
Transformer models can effectively capture longitudinal patient
trajectories~\cite{ref1,ref5}. However, the majority of this
work targets clinical outcome prediction---mortality, ICU
readmission, and disease onset~\cite{ref5,ref6,ref7}---rather
than workflow timing. Concurrently, agentic AI architectures,
in which autonomous agents reason and act toward clinical goals
in a coordinated manner, have been proposed for modular
decision support~\cite{ref8,ref10}. Yet implementations
combining learned temporal modeling with agentic orchestration
for clinical workflow delay analysis are absent from the
literature.

This paper addresses this gap with ACWIS, whose principal
contributions are:
\begin{itemize}
  \item A trigger--laboratory alignment pipeline with a
    three-level fallback strategy that maximizes delay-label
    coverage across heterogeneous ICU admissions.
  \item A two-layer LSTM delay prediction model trained on
    ten temporal features with patient-level data splitting
    to prevent information leakage.
  \item A LangGraph-based agentic dual-pipeline architecture
    implementing reactive deviation detection (post-event)
    and proactive early warning (pre-event)---the first
    such framework for ICU diagnostic delay detection.
  \item Validation on the MIMIC-IV dataset across 703,808
    trigger-level records from diverse ICU patient cohorts.
\end{itemize}

Section~\ref{sec:related} reviews related work.
Section~\ref{sec:problem} formalizes the problem.
Section~\ref{sec:system} presents the proposed system.
Section~\ref{sec:experiments} reports experimental results.
Section~\ref{sec:discussion} discusses findings and limitations.
Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes the paper.

