\subsection{Cohort Construction}

The patient cohort is extracted from MIMIC-IV~\cite{mimiciv}
by retaining ICU stays with cardiac or respiratory instability
diagnoses. Cardiac cases are identified by ICD-10 prefixes
I20--I25 (ischemic heart disease) and I47--I50 (arrhythmia
and heart failure); respiratory cases by J44~(COPD), J45
(asthma), J96~(respiratory failure), and J18~(pneumonia).

\subsection{Trigger Extraction and Delay Computation}

\subsubsection{Trigger criteria}
A trigger event is generated whenever any of the following
physiological instability thresholds is exceeded, consistent
with standard ICU early warning scoring: heart rate
$>$\,100\,bpm; mean arterial pressure $<$\,65\,mmHg;
peripheral oxygen saturation $<$\,90\,\%; respiratory rate
$>$\,30\,br\,min$^{-1}$.

\subsubsection{Three-level laboratory alignment}
The delay $d_j$ is computed by locating the first relevant
laboratory event after $\tau_j$ using three fallback levels:
(1)~a trigger-specific panel (cardiac biomarker panel for
HR\_HIGH and MAP\_LOW; arterial blood gas panel for SPO2\_LOW
and RR\_HIGH); (2)~a twelve-item common ICU laboratory panel;
and (3)~any laboratory event in the monitoring window.
A minimum two-hour window excludes near-zero delays from
pre-ordered tests.

\subsection{Feature Engineering and Sequence Construction}

Ten temporal features are extracted per trigger event, as
listed in Table~\ref{tab:features}. Missing vital signs are
imputed via per-stay forward/backward fill then trigger-type
median imputation. Features are cast to float32 and
standardized using a \texttt{StandardScaler} fitted solely
on training data. The regression target is
\begin{equation}
  y_j = \log(1 + 60\,d_j),
  \label{eq:target}
\end{equation}
converting delay to minutes and applying a log-transform to
stabilize the right-skewed distribution. Predictions are
recovered as $\hat{d}_j=(\exp(\hat{y}_j)-1)/60$.

Input sequences are constructed by a sliding window of $W=5$
consecutive triggers per stay, yielding tensors of shape
$5\times10$.

