\subsection{Dataset}

Experiments use MIMIC-IV (v1.4)~\cite{mimiciv}, a
de-identified credentialed-access ICU database from Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center, comprising data from multiple ICU
types. Five tables are used: \texttt{icustays},
\texttt{admissions}, \texttt{diagnoses\_icd},
\texttt{chartevents}, and \texttt{labevents}. After cohort
filtering, trigger extraction, and three-level alignment,
703,808 trigger-level records are produced; 269,664 carry
valid delay labels. Removal of the top 1\% of delays as
outliers yields 266,977 records for training and evaluation.

Table~\ref{tab:trigdist} reports the trigger-type distribution.
SPO2\_LOW episodes show the longest mean delay (3.41\,h),
while HR\_HIGH episodes are resolved most promptly (2.11\,h),
consistent with established clinical urgency hierarchies
in ICU early warning systems.

