The $R^2$ of $-$0.036 reflects the stochastic nature of ICU
laboratory response timing, where unobserved operational
factors---phlebotomist availability, analyzer throughput, and
shift transitions---dominate outcome variance beyond what
EHR-derived features can explain. This behavior is consistent
with prior stochastic clinical event timing
studies~\cite{ref7}. The clinical value of ACWIS lies in the
deviation signal produced by the agentic pipeline rather than
in absolute point accuracy.

\subsection{MAE Analysis by Delay Magnitude}

Fig.~\ref{fig:bucket} stratifies MAE by true-delay bucket.
The model achieves lowest error on short-delay cases:
MAE\,=\,47\,min for delays under 1\,h ($n$\,=\,9,265) and
MAE\,=\,36\,min for 1--3\,h delays ($n$\,=\,10,504), which
together comprise 82\% of labeled records. Error increases
progressively for longer delays---a well-established
characteristic of regression-to-the-mean under high label
variance~\cite{ref5}. For delays exceeding 12\,h
($n$\,=\,454, 1.8\% of labeled records), MAE reaches
770\,min; these rare extreme events do not materially affect
the proactive alerting capability of the system, which
responds to the deviation signal rather than the absolute
predicted value.

