%%===========================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
%%===========================================================

\subsection{Clinical Significance}

ACWIS reframes diagnostic delay detection as deviation from a
\textit{learned, patient-conditioned} temporal expectation
rather than a fixed threshold. This distinction matters
clinically: a two-hour laboratory delay for a stable patient
recovering overnight and a two-hour delay following an acute
oxygen desaturation event carry fundamentally different
clinical implications. By conditioning on vital sign
trajectory, trigger type, time of day, and patient
demographics, the LSTM model captures this context without
expert-defined rules.

The proactive pipeline's pre-event alerting capability
represents the primary practical contribution: it converts a
learned temporal prediction into actionable clinical
intelligence before a delay has fully materialized. A
conventional fixed-threshold system operating at the same
moment would not raise an alert because no static deadline
would yet have elapsed.

\subsection{Prediction Performance in Context}

The 2.3\% MAE improvement over the mean predictor confirms
that the LSTM captures meaningful temporal structure in
trigger--delay sequences. The negative $R^2$ is a known
characteristic of stochastic process timing prediction in
healthcare~\cite{ref7}: laboratory response time is
substantially governed by operational factors exogenous to
the EHR record. This does not indicate model failure; it
indicates that absolute delay prediction is inherently
limited by unobservable confounders, and that the clinical
evaluation criterion should be the timeliness and correctness
of the deviation signal, which the agent pipeline evaluation
validates.

The MAE stratification by delay bucket (Fig.~\ref{fig:bucket})
is important for clinical contextualization: the model
performs well precisely for the delays that occur most
frequently (under 3\,h, 82\% of cases), while degrading for
rare extreme delays that are difficult to predict from
vital-sign features alone.

\subsection{Limitations}

\textit{Single-center validation.}~MIMIC-IV originates from
a single institution; workflow norms differ across ICU
environments. Retraining on local data is required before
clinical deployment.

\textit{Operational confounders.}~Laboratory response timing
depends on staffing patterns, equipment availability, and
shift scheduling---factors not present in the EHR. This
places a ceiling on achievable regression accuracy
independent of model sophistication.

\textit{Fixed trigger thresholds.}~Population-level
instability thresholds do not account for individual
patient baselines; adaptive, patient-specific thresholding
would improve trigger specificity.

\textit{Agent evaluation scope.}~The current agentic
evaluation uses representative case illustrations. A
rigorous evaluation requires aggregate metrics over all
test stays---planned as immediate future work.

\textit{Severity boundary validation.}~The boundaries
in~\eqref{eq:sev} are defined empirically; prospective
mapping to clinical outcome rates per severity tier is
required before patient-facing deployment.

\subsection{Future Work}

Planned extensions include: (1)~nursing note and medication
administration event integration as additional temporal
features; (2)~Transformer-based sequence encoding for
longer-range trigger dependencies; (3)~attention-weight
visualization for feature-level explainability in the
monitoring dashboard; and (4)~prospective clinical
validation in a live ICU environment.

%%===========================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
%%===========================================================

This paper presented ACWIS, an agentic clinical workflow
intelligence system for detecting diagnostic delays in ICU
electronic health records without predefined temporal rules.
The system integrates a five-stage preprocessing pipeline, a
two-layer LSTM delay prediction model, and a LangGraph-based
dual reactive--proactive agentic multi-agent architecture.
Evaluated on MIMIC-IV across 703,808 trigger-level records,
ACWIS achieves MAE 89.93\,min---a 2.3\% improvement over the
mean-predictor baseline---with best performance on the most
frequent delay range (under 3\,h, MAE\,$<$\,50\,min).
The proactive pipeline demonstrates pre-event alerting
capability, raising severity alerts before laboratory
completion. The framework is fully data-driven, modular by
LangGraph design, and delivers structured severity
assessments and LLM-generated clinical explanations.

To the best of the authors' knowledge, ACWIS is the first
system to combine learned LSTM-based delay prediction with
LangGraph-orchestrated dual reactive--proactive agentic
monitoring and LLM explanation generation for ICU clinical
workflow intelligence.

